**Promise vs Observable**

| | Promise | Observable |
|---|---|---|
| **Values** | Single value (or error) | Stream of 0..N values over time |
| **Eagerness** | **Eager** — executes immediately on creation | **Lazy** — executes only when subscribed |
| **Cancellation** | Not natively cancellable | Unsubscribe cancels execution |
| **Multicast** | Always shared (one resolution) | Unicast by default (each subscriber triggers a new execution); can be multicast via operators |
| **Built-in?** | Yes — native JS (`Promise`) | No — requires a library (RxJS, most commonly) |
| **Operators** | `.then()`, `.catch()`, `.finally()` | Rich operator chain (`map`, `filter`, `switchMap`, `debounceTime`, hundreds more) |
| **Retry** | Manual | Built-in (`retry`, `retryWhen`) |

**When to use which:**

- **Promise** — single async result (HTTP request, reading a file, `async/await` workflows). It's the default choice.
- **Observable** — streams of events (WebSocket messages, user input, real-time data), or when you need cancellation, composition of multiple async sources, or backpressure control.

**Quick code contrast:**

```js
// Promise — fires immediately, resolves once
const p = new Promise(resolve => {
  console.log('running');       // prints immediately
  resolve(42);
});
p.then(v => console.log(v));   // 42

// Observable — nothing happens until subscribe()
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
const o = new Observable(subscriber => {
  console.log('running');       // prints only on subscribe
  subscriber.next(1);
  subscriber.next(2);
  subscriber.complete();
});
const sub = o.subscribe(v => console.log(v)); // 1, 2
sub.unsubscribe(); // cancels if still active
```

**Key mental model:** A Promise is like ordering one package — it's on its way whether you want it or not. An Observable is like a Netflix stream — nothing plays until you hit play, it keeps sending frames, and you can stop anytime.

**Promise vs Observable**

| | Promise | Observable |
|---|---|---|
| **Values** | Single value (or error) | Stream of 0+ values over time |
| **Eagerness** | **Eager** — executes immediately on creation | **Lazy** — executes only when subscribed |
| **Cancellation** | Not natively cancellable | Unsubscribe cancels execution |
| **Multicast** | Always shared (one resolution) | Unicast by default (each subscriber gets independent execution) |
| **Built-in?** | Yes — native JS | No — requires a library (RxJS, most commonly) |
| **Operators** | `.then()`, `.catch()`, `.finally()` | Rich operator chain (`map`, `filter`, `debounceTime`, `switchMap`, hundreds more) |
| **Retry** | Manual | Built-in (`retry`, `retryWhen`) |

**When to use which:**

- **Promise** — single async result (HTTP request, reading a file, `async/await` flows)
- **Observable** — event streams, WebSockets, user input, anything where you need combination/transformation of multiple async events, or cancellation matters

**Quick code comparison:**

```js
// Promise — fires immediately, resolves once
const p = new Promise(resolve => {
  setTimeout(() => resolve('done'), 1000);
});
p.then(v => console.log(v)); // "done"

// Observable — nothing happens until subscribe()
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
const o = new Observable(subscriber => {
  subscriber.next(1);
  subscriber.next(2);
  setTimeout(() => { subscriber.next(3); subscriber.complete(); }, 1000);
});
const sub = o.subscribe(v => console.log(v)); // 1, 2, ...3
sub.unsubscribe(); // cancels — 3 never emits
```

**Key gotcha:** A Promise's executor runs even if nobody calls `.then()`. An Observable does literally nothing until `.subscribe()` — this makes Observables safer for expensive operations you might not always need.
